JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1155
EP  - 1177
VL  - 53
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2012.00715.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Motivated by widely publicized concerns that there are ?too many? plans, we structurally estimate (and validate) an equilibrium model of the Medicare Part D market to study the welfare impacts of two feasible, similar-sized approaches for reducing choice. One reduces the maximum number of firm offerings regionally; the other removes plans providing donut hole coverage?consumers? most valued dimension. We find welfare losses are far smaller when coupled with elimination of a dimension of differentiation. We illustrate our findings? relevance under current health care reforms, and consider the merits of instead imposing ex ante competition for entry.
ER  - 

